/*
BONEYARD: Development notes — not for production draft.
Original concept: A photographer who loses her sight discovers
that she sees more now than she ever did with her eyes open.
The lighthouse is a metaphor for the self: tall, isolated,
built to guide others, abandoned when the ships stop coming.
*/

# ACT ONE — THE LAST ASSIGNMENT

= Synopsis: Maya arrives at the lighthouse she was born in.
= It will be demolished at dawn. She has one night to document it.
= She has been blind for three years. She does not consider this an obstacle.

FADE IN:

INT. TAXI — MOVING — DUSK

*The last light of day bleeds through the windshield.* A camera bag occupies the seat like a passenger. Beside it, MAYA OSEI (42, calm the way deep water is calm — not still, just unfathomable) runs her fingers across the body of a Leica she'll never use to see again.

The TAXI DRIVER glances in the mirror.

TAXI DRIVER
You sure about this? Road's closed
past the turnoff. Storm coming.

MAYA
(the patience of someone
who has stopped explaining herself)
I know about the storm. That's why
I'm going tonight.

[[Character note: Maya never performs blindness. She simply inhabits the world
differently. Directors: resist the urge to signal her disability through hesitation.
She hesitates for the same reasons anyone does. Not because she can't see.]]

TAXI DRIVER
There's nothing out there. Lighthouse
hasn't been active since —

MAYA
Nineteen eighty-four. I was born
the same year they turned it off.
We've been going dark together
ever since.

Beat. The driver understands he's in the presence of something he can't categorize and returns his eyes to the road.

EXT. COASTAL ROAD — DUSK — CONTINUOUS

> TO PLACE: CAPE MERIDIAN, MAINE — ONE HOUR BEFORE DARK <

The taxi dwindles to a pair of tail-lights against the enormous indifference of the Atlantic. Maya stands on the gravel, head tilted, reading the wind.

She opens a small device on her wrist. A soft series of *TONES* — spatial mapping, LiDAR translated into sound frequencies only she has learned to interpret.

To her: the lighthouse is a column of low, steady sound, pulling northwest. Eighty feet. Stone. Hollow.

She has not been here in eleven years. The tones tell her it hasn't changed.

She walks toward it without hesitation.

## THE LIGHTHOUSE

= The lighthouse is not a location. It is a character.
= It holds its secrets the way old stone holds cold: deep and long.

EXT. LIGHTHOUSE BASE — DUSK

SUPER: "CAPE MERIDIAN LIGHT — BUILT 1887 — DECOMMISSIONED 1984 — SCHEDULED FOR DEMOLITION, DAWN"

The door is unlocked. Someone expected her.

INT. LIGHTHOUSE — GROUND FLOOR — NIGHT

She enters. The LiDAR tones shift, mapping the room she's never seen and yet somehow knows. An old OIL DRUM. A WORKBENCH. Tools arranged with the precision of a person who could not afford to misplace them.

And photographs. Hundreds of them. Pinned to every surface.

Maya cannot see them. She reaches out and touches the nearest one — not to see it, but to feel the paper, the chemical ghost of silver halide under her fingertips.

MAYA
(to no one — or to everything)
Who hung these?

No answer. Only the storm beginning its conversation with the windows.

She sets up. Deliberate. Practiced. She mounts the Leica on a tripod by muscle memory, attaches the LiDAR sensor to the hot shoe, activates it.

INSERT: The camera screen shows a wireframe topology of the room — stone walls, beams, the photographs rendered as rectangular patches of contrast. This is what Maya sees.

She *feels* the room through the camera.

MAYA (CONT'D)
(beginning to work)
Okay. Tell me everything.

# ACT TWO — WHAT THE DARK KNOWS

## FLASHBACK — ELEVEN YEARS AGO

MATCH CUT TO:

INT. LIGHTHOUSE — GROUND FLOOR — DAY (FLASHBACK)

*The same room, but saturated. Sunlight.* A younger MAYA (31, eyes wide open, a different kind of certainty) moves through the space with a camera to her eye, SHOOTING.

Across the room, her FATHER (65, architect's hands, a lighthouse keeper's silence) watches her work.

MAYA (V.O.)
I used to think I understood light because
I could measure it. F-stop. ISO. Shutter speed.
As if light were a problem to be solved
rather than a language to be learned.

She photographs her father. He doesn't pose. He simply is.

MAYA (V.O.) (CONT'D)
He tried to tell me. Every time I visited.

FATHER
(to young Maya, quietly)
You look at things. That's different
from seeing them.

YOUNG MAYA
(not looking up from viewfinder)
I see fine, Dad.

He watches her miss the point. He smiles with the tenderness of a man who knows the lesson will arrive on its own schedule.

FATHER
(to himself)
Not yet.

DISSOLVE TO:

## RETURN TO PRESENT

INT. LIGHTHOUSE — GROUND FLOOR — NIGHT (PRESENT)

Back to Maya. Same room. Same photographs. Different eyes.

MAYA (O.S.)
(calling upward into the stairwell)
Is someone up there?

Silence. Then:

FOOTSTEPS. Slow. Measured.

THADDEUS (V.O.)
(from above, old voice, warm as worn wood)
Been wondering when you'd get here.

Maya doesn't reach for a weapon. She reaches for her camera.

MAYA
Who are you?

THADDEUS (V.O.)
Name's Thaddeus. I was the last keeper.
After the service let me go, I just...
didn't leave.

Maya tilts her head. The LiDAR maps his descent through the floor above — an elderly man, slight, cautious on the stairs.

MAYA
You've been living here?

THADDEUS (V.O.)
Living might be generous.
I've been keeping the light on
for people who don't know they need it.

## THE CONVERSATION AT THE TOP

INT. LIGHTHOUSE — LAMP ROOM — NIGHT

*They sit with the dark Atlantic below them and the storm pressing its face against the glass.* The great lamp — dead since '84 — looms behind them, massive, patient, waiting for permission.

THADDEUS and MAYA. Two people who found a way to see when the light failed.

A moment of dual presence — of equal weight:

MAYA                            THADDEUS
So you knew my father.          Your father built the photographs.

They register the coincidence at the same time.

MAYA
He built them?

THADDEUS
Printed them all himself.
Pinned them up so the room would remember
what the light looked like when it worked.
Forty years of mornings.

Beat.

MAYA
He never told me.

THADDEUS
He told you in the only way
he knew how.

He gets up. Moves to the lamp housing. Places both hands on it.

THADDEUS (CONT'D)
You want to photograph something real
before they knock this down?

She hears something in his voice.

MAYA
You're going to turn it on.

THADDEUS
Been saving the oil thirty-seven years
for the right reason.

# ACT THREE — THE WEIGHT OF LIGHT

## SERIES OF SHOTS — THE LAMP COMES BACK TO LIFE

— Thaddeus' hands on the old mechanism, trembling with age and purpose.

— The wick catching. A small miracle. An inch of gold in the dark.

— Maya's LiDAR mapping the growing light as *tones rising in frequency* — the sound of a room brightening.

— The Fresnel lens beginning its rotation. Light fractured into a thousand pieces, each one landing somewhere in the dark.

— On the photographs: her father's forty years of mornings, finally illuminated.

— Outside, through the glass, the beam sweeping the storm-dark Atlantic. Something ancient and necessary resumed.

— Maya shooting. Not looking at her camera. *Feeling* the light with her whole body.

THADDEUS (O.S.)
(barely above a whisper)
There she is.

## THE LAST FRAME

POV — MAYA'S LIDAR

*Not an image. A topology.* The lamp room rendered in sound-frequencies, the rotating beam translated into pulses across her wristband. This is what she photographs. Not the light. The shape of the light. The space the light makes possible.

And in the wireframe: her father's photographs on the wall below, and Thaddeus at the lamp, and beyond the glass, the sea.

She presses the shutter.

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. LIGHTHOUSE — DAWN

The demolition crew arrives to find the lighthouse lit. They stop their machines.

No one gives the order to proceed.

INT. LIGHTHOUSE — LAMP ROOM — DAWN

The beam still turns. Maya is gone. The photographs remain.

On the workbench: a single print, still wet, still developing. The wireframe topology of a room full of light. Beautiful in the way that only truth is beautiful — because it doesn't try to be.

> THE WEIGHT OF LIGHT <

FADE TO BLACK.

